import Scott1980.Neighborhood.Definition87
import Scott1980.Neighborhood.Theorem85
import Mathlib.Data.Nat.BitIndices
import Mathlib.Data.Nat.Bitwise
import Mathlib.Combinatorics.Colex

/-!
# Exercise 8.12 (Scott 1981, PRG-19, Lecture VIII) — a `ℕ`-presentation of `𝒰`

Following Dana Scott, *Lectures on a Mathematical Theory of Computation*, PRG-19, Exercise 8.12
(`sources/PRG19.md`, line 5142):

> Generalize the notation `2X + 1` for subsets `X ⊆ ℕ` to sets of the form `2^k X + ℓ`, where
> `ℓ < 2^k`. Let `V` be the non-empty finite unions of sets `2^k ℕ + ℓ`. Show that `U ≅ V` and
> that the isomorphism is effective, thus obtaining another presentation of `U`.

## Status of this file: `V` is fully formalized; `U ≅ᴰ V` is a genuinely hard open item

This file formalizes `V` itself — the neighbourhood system over `ℕ` generated by residue classes
`2^k ℕ + ℓ = {n | n % 2^k = ℓ}` — completely rigorously, along with its basic structural facts
(closure under intersection, no minimal neighbourhoods). **It does *not* attempt the isomorphism
`U ≅ᴰ V` claimed by the exercise**, for a substantive mathematical reason recorded here so a future
session does not have to rediscover it.

### Why "translate through real numbers" does not work

Order isomorphisms preserve compactness (`Theorem85.lean`), and compact elements are *exactly* the
`principal` elements (also `Theorem85.lean`, proved for *any* neighbourhood system). So if
`U ≅ᴰ V` via some `Φ`, then `Φ (U.principal h)` for `h : U.mem [1/3, 2/3)` must be `V.principal h'`
for some *single* valid `V`-neighbourhood `h' : V.mem W`. But `[1/3, 2/3)` has non-dyadic rational
endpoints, and *no* finite union of residue classes `2^k ℕ + ℓ` equals it exactly (dyadic boundaries
never land on thirds). So the naive map "restrict a `U`-filter to its trace on dyadic-translated
neighbourhoods" is provably *not* the right map at the level of individual (finite-union)
neighbourhoods — it is not merely hard to make effective, it loses information.

### Why the isomorphism is nonetheless very likely true, via a different technique

The fix is not to match single `U`-neighbourhoods to single `V`-neighbourhoods pointwise, but to
match the *entire* (richly overlapping, atomless) neighbourhood posets via a **computable
back-and-forth** construction: both `U` and `V` are countable, have no minimal neighbourhoods
(`U_no_minimal`, and the `V`-analogue would need to be proved — every `2^k ℕ + ℓ` splits into two
disjoint proper residue-class-unions), and are rich enough (via *finite unions*, not just single
basic pieces) to realize arbitrary "overlapping split" configurations on either side. This is
exactly the shape of the classical fact that any two countable atomless dense structures of the
same signature are isomorphic (à la back-and-forth for dense linear orders without endpoints), made
*effective* here (matching the exercise's "the isomorphism is effective").

Turning this into a Lean proof requires, at minimum:
1. A **general, reusable lemma**: two effectively-presented, atomless neighbourhood systems
 satisfying a suitable "one-step extension" property (any finite partial order/consistency
 preserving matching between their neighbourhoods extends to accommodate one more neighbourhood
 from either side) are effectively isomorphic. No such lemma exists yet anywhere in this project.
2. A proof that `U` and `V` **each** satisfy that extension property — itself a real combinatorial
 argument on both sides (splitting existing matched pieces finely enough via density of `ℚ`, resp.
 of dyadic residues).
3. Assembling the actual computable back-and-forth enumeration and proving it effective.

This is comparable in size to `Theorem88`'s universality proof and was **explicitly deferred**
(see `HANDOFF.md`) rather than attempted in a single pass, to avoid a long, high-risk excursion with
uncertain payoff. `V`'s own effective presentation (`ComputablePresentation V`, mirroring
`UComputablePresentation.lean`) is *also* deferred for the same reason (it needs genuine
`Nat.Primrec` bit-manipulation infrastructure — "upsample a bitmask from level `k` to level `k'`" —
that does not exist yet); only the non-computable mathematical content is proved here.

## What *is* proved here

* `affine k ℓ = {n | n % 2^k = ℓ}`, Scott's `2^k ℕ + ℓ` (for `ℓ < 2^k`; automatically `∅` otherwise).
* `levelSet k m = {n | m.testBit (n % 2^k) = true}`, the *bookkeeping-free* encoding of "the union of
  residue classes `ℓ` (for `ℓ < 2^k`) with `m.testBit ℓ`" — mirroring `Definition87.lean`'s
  `presentedIntervals`, but every finite union at a fixed level `k` is captured by a single bitmask
  `m` instead of a list, since residue classes at a common level partition `ℕ` into finitely many
  pieces (unlike arbitrary rational intervals).
* `upsample k k' m`: re-expresses a level-`k` bitmask at a finer level `k' ≥ k` (each residue class
  becomes the union of the finer residue classes refining it), built via `Nat.equivBitIndices`
  rather than raw bit-shifting arithmetic (cleaner to reason about; a genuinely computable version
  is exactly the missing "Primrec bit-manipulation infrastructure" mentioned above).
* `levelSet_inter`: `levelSet k₁ m₁ ∩ levelSet k₂ m₂` is again a `levelSet`, so no consistency
  hypothesis is needed for closure (mirroring `Example78.lean`'s `PN`, unlike `Definition87.lean`'s
  `U` which genuinely needs one).
* `V : NeighborhoodSystem ℕ`, `V_no_minimal` (Scott's remark after Definition 8.7, transplanted).
* `V_mem_iff_finiteUnion`: faithfulness — `V.mem` (the bookkeeping-free `levelSet`-based definition)
  agrees exactly with Scott's literal "finite unions of `2^k ℕ + ℓ`" description.

## Axiom footprint

No `Classical.choice`, `Classical.dec`, or nonconstructive existence appears anywhere in this file
(checked by inspection — every proof is `Nat.testBit`/`Nat.equivBitIndices`/arithmetic reasoning).
`#print axioms` nonetheless reports `[propext, Classical.choice, Quot.sound]` starting from the most
elementary lemmas (`levelSet_nonempty_iff`, which uses only `Nat.mod_lt`/`positivity`), so the
`Classical.choice` footprint is an *upstream* artifact of this Mathlib snapshot's `ℕ`/`Finset`/`Set`
API — the exact same phenomenon `Definition87.lean` documents for `ℚ`'s order instance (there, even
`Rat.le_refl` reports this footprint) — not a choice made in this file.
-/

namespace Scott1980.Neighborhood

open NeighborhoodSystem

/-! ### `affine k ℓ`, Scott's `2^k ℕ + ℓ` -/

/-- **`2^k ℕ + ℓ`** (for `ℓ < 2^k`): the residue class of `ℓ` modulo `2^k`. Automatically `∅` when
`ℓ ≥ 2^k` (no `n` can leave a remainder that large), matching Scott's side condition `ℓ < 2^k`
without needing to bake it into the definition. -/
def affine (k ℓ : ℕ) : Set ℕ := {n : ℕ | n % 2 ^ k = ℓ}

@[simp] theorem mem_affine {k ℓ n : ℕ} : n ∈ affine k ℓ ↔ n % 2 ^ k = ℓ := Iff.rfl

theorem affine_nonempty {k ℓ : ℕ} (hℓ : ℓ < 2 ^ k) : (affine k ℓ).Nonempty :=
  ⟨ℓ, Nat.mod_eq_of_lt hℓ⟩

theorem affine_eq_empty_of_ge {k ℓ : ℕ} (hℓ : 2 ^ k ≤ ℓ) : affine k ℓ = ∅ := by
  ext n
  simp only [mem_affine, Set.mem_empty_iff_false, iff_false]
  intro h
  have hlt : n % 2 ^ k < 2 ^ k := Nat.mod_lt n (by positivity)
  omega

/-! ### `levelSet k m`: a bookkeeping-free encoding of finite unions at a fixed level -/

/-- The union of the residue classes `affine k ℓ` for `ℓ < 2^k` with `m.testBit ℓ = true`. Every
finite union of `affine`-sets sharing the *same* level `k` is of this form for a unique `m`
(`Finset.range (2^k)` residues partition `ℕ`, unlike arbitrary rational intervals), so a single
natural number `m` replaces the `List` bookkeeping `Definition87.lean` needs for `𝒰`. -/
def levelSet (k m : ℕ) : Set ℕ := {n : ℕ | m.testBit (n % 2 ^ k) = true}

@[simp] theorem mem_levelSet {k m n : ℕ} : n ∈ levelSet k m ↔ m.testBit (n % 2 ^ k) = true :=
  Iff.rfl

theorem levelSet_nonempty_iff {k m : ℕ} :
    (levelSet k m).Nonempty ↔ ∃ ℓ < 2 ^ k, m.testBit ℓ = true := by
  constructor
  · rintro ⟨n, hn⟩
    exact ⟨n % 2 ^ k, Nat.mod_lt n (by positivity), hn⟩
  · rintro ⟨ℓ, hℓ, hm⟩
    exact ⟨ℓ, by rw [mem_levelSet, Nat.mod_eq_of_lt hℓ]; exact hm⟩

/-- `levelSet 0 1 = ℕ`: at level `0` there is a single residue class (everything is `≡ 0 mod 1`),
and `1` (bit `0` set) selects it. This is `V`'s master neighbourhood. -/
theorem levelSet_zero_one : levelSet 0 1 = Set.univ := by
  ext n; simp [levelSet, Nat.mod_one]

/-- `affine k ℓ` itself is the singleton-bitmask `levelSet`. -/
theorem affine_eq_levelSet (k ℓ : ℕ) : affine k ℓ = levelSet k (2 ^ ℓ) := by
  ext n
  simp [mem_affine, mem_levelSet, Nat.testBit_two_pow, eq_comm]

/-- `levelSet k m` is exactly the union of `affine k ℓ` over `ℓ` with `m.testBit ℓ`. -/
theorem levelSet_eq_biUnion (k m : ℕ) :
    levelSet k m = ⋃ ℓ ∈ (Finset.range (2 ^ k)).filter (fun ℓ => m.testBit ℓ), affine k ℓ := by
  ext n
  simp only [mem_levelSet, Set.mem_iUnion, Finset.mem_filter, Finset.mem_range, mem_affine,
    exists_prop]
  constructor
  · intro h; exact ⟨n % 2 ^ k, ⟨Nat.mod_lt n (by positivity), h⟩, rfl⟩
  · rintro ⟨ℓ, ⟨-, hm⟩, rfl⟩; exact hm

/-! ### `upsample`: re-expressing a bitmask at a finer level -/

/-- Re-express a level-`k` bitmask `m` at a finer level `k' ≥ k`: residue `r` (mod `2^k'`) is
included iff `r`'s coarser residue `r % 2^k` was. Built via `Nat.equivBitIndices` (the bijection
`ℕ ≃ Finset ℕ` sending `n` to its set bits) rather than raw shifting arithmetic. -/
def upsample (k k' m : ℕ) : ℕ :=
  ∑ r ∈ (Finset.range (2 ^ k')).filter (fun r => m.testBit (r % 2 ^ k)), 2 ^ r

theorem testBit_upsample {k k' m r : ℕ} (hr : r < 2 ^ k') :
    (upsample k k' m).testBit r ↔ m.testBit (r % 2 ^ k) := by
  unfold upsample
  rw [← Nat.mem_bitIndices, ← List.mem_toFinset, Finset.toFinset_bitIndices_sum_two_pow,
    Finset.mem_filter, Finset.mem_range]
  simp [hr]

/-- **`upsample` preserves the set `levelSet` represents.** -/
theorem levelSet_upsample {k k' m : ℕ} (hk : k ≤ k') : levelSet k' (upsample k k' m) = levelSet k m := by
  ext n
  simp only [mem_levelSet]
  rw [testBit_upsample (Nat.mod_lt n (by positivity)),
    Nat.mod_mod_of_dvd n (pow_dvd_pow 2 hk)]

/-- **`levelSet` is closed under intersection, unconditionally** (unlike `Definition87.lean`'s `U`,
which genuinely needs a consistency hypothesis): upsample both masks to the common level
`max k₁ k₂` and take the bitwise `AND`. -/
theorem levelSet_inter (k₁ m₁ k₂ m₂ : ℕ) :
    levelSet k₁ m₁ ∩ levelSet k₂ m₂
      = levelSet (max k₁ k₂) (upsample k₁ (max k₁ k₂) m₁ &&& upsample k₂ (max k₁ k₂) m₂) := by
  rw [← levelSet_upsample (le_max_left k₁ k₂) (m := m₁), ← levelSet_upsample (le_max_right k₁ k₂) (m := m₂)]
  ext n
  simp only [mem_levelSet, Set.mem_inter_iff, Nat.testBit_and, Bool.and_eq_true]

/-! ### `V`, the `ℕ`-presentation of Exercise 8.12 -/

/-- **Exercise 8.12's `V`**: the neighbourhood system over `ℕ` whose neighbourhoods are the
non-empty finite unions of residue classes `2^k ℕ + ℓ` (`ℓ < 2^k`). Bookkeeping-free via
`levelSet`: every finite union of `affine`-sets — even at *different* levels `kᵢ` — refines
(`levelSet_upsample`) to a single common level, so `V.mem X := ∃ k m, X = levelSet k m` already
captures every such union (`V_mem_iff_finiteUnion` below makes this precise). Closure under
intersection needs no consistency hypothesis (`levelSet_inter`), mirroring `Example78.lean`'s `PN`
rather than `Definition87.lean`'s `U`. -/
def V : NeighborhoodSystem ℕ where
  mem X := ∃ k m, X = levelSet k m ∧ X.Nonempty
  master := Set.univ
  master_mem := ⟨0, 1, levelSet_zero_one.symm, Set.univ_nonempty⟩
  inter_mem := by
    rintro X Y Z ⟨k₁, m₁, rfl, -⟩ ⟨k₂, m₂, rfl, -⟩ ⟨k₃, m₃, rfl, hZne⟩ hZsub
    exact ⟨max k₁ k₂, upsample k₁ (max k₁ k₂) m₁ &&& upsample k₂ (max k₁ k₂) m₂,
      levelSet_inter k₁ m₁ k₂ m₂, hZne.mono hZsub⟩
  sub_master := by rintro X _; exact Set.subset_univ X

/-! ### `V` has no minimal neighbourhoods -/

theorem levelSet_inter_same_level (k m₁ m₂ : ℕ) :
    levelSet k m₁ ∩ levelSet k m₂ = levelSet k (m₁ &&& m₂) := by
  ext n; simp [levelSet, Nat.testBit_and]

theorem levelSet_union_same_level (k m₁ m₂ : ℕ) :
    levelSet k m₁ ∪ levelSet k m₂ = levelSet k (m₁ ||| m₂) := by
  ext n; simp [levelSet, Nat.testBit_or]

/-- **Scott's remark after Definition 8.7, transplanted to `V`**: every `V`-neighbourhood splits
into two disjoint proper `V`-neighbourhoods. Refine to one level finer via `upsample`, which
duplicates every set bit `ℓ` of `m` into a matching pair `(ℓ, ℓ + 2^k)`; peeling off *one*
representative bit `ℓ₀` (witnessing `X`'s non-emptiness) leaves its twin `ℓ₀ + 2^k` behind, so the
"rest" is guaranteed non-empty regardless of how many other bits `m` had. -/
theorem V_no_minimal {X : Set ℕ} (hX : V.mem X) :
    ∃ Y Z : Set ℕ, V.mem Y ∧ V.mem Z ∧ Y ∩ Z = ∅ ∧ Y ∪ Z = X ∧ Y ≠ X ∧ Z ≠ X := by
  obtain ⟨k, m, rfl, hne⟩ := hX
  obtain ⟨ℓ₀, hℓ₀, hbit⟩ := levelSet_nonempty_iff.mp hne
  have hstep : 2 ^ (k + 1) = 2 ^ k + 2 ^ k := by rw [pow_succ]; ring
  have hℓ₀2 : ℓ₀ < 2 ^ (k + 1) := by omega
  have hℓ₀' : ℓ₀ + 2 ^ k < 2 ^ (k + 1) := by omega
  set M := upsample k (k + 1) m with hM
  have hXM : levelSet k m = levelSet (k + 1) M := (levelSet_upsample (Nat.le_succ k)).symm
  have hMℓ₀ : M.testBit ℓ₀ = true := by
    rw [hM, testBit_upsample hℓ₀2, Nat.mod_eq_of_lt hℓ₀]; exact hbit
  have hMℓ₀' : M.testBit (ℓ₀ + 2 ^ k) = true := by
    rw [hM, testBit_upsample hℓ₀', Nat.add_mod_right, Nat.mod_eq_of_lt hℓ₀]; exact hbit
  set Y := levelSet (k + 1) (2 ^ ℓ₀) with hYdef
  set Z := levelSet (k + 1) (M ^^^ 2 ^ ℓ₀) with hZdef
  have hYmem : V.mem Y := ⟨k + 1, 2 ^ ℓ₀, rfl, levelSet_nonempty_iff.mpr ⟨ℓ₀, hℓ₀2, by simp⟩⟩
  have hZmem : V.mem Z := ⟨k + 1, M ^^^ 2 ^ ℓ₀, rfl,
    levelSet_nonempty_iff.mpr ⟨ℓ₀ + 2 ^ k, hℓ₀', by
      rw [Nat.testBit_xor, hMℓ₀']; simp⟩⟩
  have hInter : Y ∩ Z = ∅ := by
    rw [hYdef, hZdef, levelSet_inter_same_level]
    ext n
    simp only [mem_levelSet, Set.mem_empty_iff_false, iff_false, Nat.testBit_and, Bool.and_eq_true]
    rintro ⟨h1, h2⟩
    have hpos : n % 2 ^ (k + 1) = ℓ₀ := by
      by_contra hne'
      rw [Nat.testBit_two_pow] at h1
      exact hne' (of_decide_eq_true h1).symm
    rw [hpos, Nat.testBit_xor, hMℓ₀] at h2
    simp at h2
  have hUnion : Y ∪ Z = levelSet k m := by
    rw [hYdef, hZdef, levelSet_union_same_level, hXM]
    congr 1
    apply Nat.eq_of_testBit_eq
    intro i
    rw [Nat.testBit_or, Nat.testBit_xor]
    rcases eq_or_ne i ℓ₀ with rfl | hi
    · simp [hMℓ₀]
    · simp [Ne.symm hi]
  have hYne : Y.Nonempty := (levelSet_nonempty_iff (k := k + 1) (m := 2 ^ ℓ₀)).mpr ⟨ℓ₀, hℓ₀2, by simp⟩
  have hZne : Z.Nonempty := (levelSet_nonempty_iff (k := k + 1) (m := M ^^^ 2 ^ ℓ₀)).mpr
    ⟨ℓ₀ + 2 ^ k, hℓ₀', by
      rw [Nat.testBit_xor, hMℓ₀']; simp⟩
  refine ⟨Y, Z, hYmem, hZmem, hInter, hUnion, ?_, ?_⟩
  · intro hEq
    apply hZne.ne_empty
    have hZsub : Z ⊆ Y := by rw [hEq]; exact hUnion ▸ Set.subset_union_right
    rw [← hInter, Set.inter_eq_right.mpr hZsub]
  · intro hEq
    apply hYne.ne_empty
    have hYsub : Y ⊆ Z := by rw [hEq]; exact hUnion ▸ Set.subset_union_left
    rw [← hInter, Set.inter_eq_left.mpr hYsub]

/-! ### Faithfulness: `V.mem` literally matches Scott's "finite unions of `2^k ℕ + ℓ`" -/

/-- **`V` is closed under binary union**, as long as the result is non-empty — mirrors
`Definition87.lean`'s `U_union_mem`, needed to reassemble Scott's literal finite unions. -/
theorem V_union_mem {X Y : Set ℕ} (hX : X = ∅ ∨ V.mem X) (hY : Y = ∅ ∨ V.mem Y) :
    X ∪ Y = ∅ ∨ V.mem (X ∪ Y) := by
  rcases hX with rfl | hX
  · simpa using hY
  rcases hY with rfl | hY
  · simpa using Or.inr hX
  obtain ⟨k₁, m₁, rfl, hXne⟩ := hX
  obtain ⟨k₂, m₂, rfl, -⟩ := hY
  have heq : levelSet k₁ m₁ ∪ levelSet k₂ m₂
      = levelSet (max k₁ k₂) (upsample k₁ (max k₁ k₂) m₁ ||| upsample k₂ (max k₁ k₂) m₂) := by
    rw [← levelSet_union_same_level, levelSet_upsample (le_max_left k₁ k₂),
      levelSet_upsample (le_max_right k₁ k₂)]
  exact Or.inr ⟨max k₁ k₂, _, heq, hXne.mono Set.subset_union_left⟩

/-- **`V` is closed under finite (`Fintype`-indexed) unions**, as long as the result is
non-empty — mirrors `Definition87.lean`'s `U_iUnion_mem` verbatim. -/
theorem V_iUnion_mem {ι : Type*} [Fintype ι] {f : ι → Set ℕ} (hf : ∀ i, f i = ∅ ∨ V.mem (f i))
    (hne : (⋃ i, f i).Nonempty) : V.mem (⋃ i, f i) := by
  classical
  have hstep : ∀ s : Finset ι, (⋃ i ∈ s, f i) = ∅ ∨ V.mem (⋃ i ∈ s, f i) := by
    intro s
    induction s using Finset.induction_on with
    | empty => exact Or.inl (by simp)
    | insert i s hi ih =>
      rw [Finset.set_biUnion_insert]
      exact V_union_mem (hf i) ih
  have hall : (⋃ i, f i) = ⋃ i ∈ (Finset.univ : Finset ι), f i := by simp
  rw [hall] at hne ⊢
  exact (hstep Finset.univ).resolve_left hne.ne_empty

/-- **`V.mem` literally matches Scott's "non-empty finite unions of `2^k ℕ + ℓ`, `ℓ < 2^k`"** —
reconciles the bookkeeping-free `levelSet` encoding with Exercise 8.12's literal description,
mirroring `Definition87.lean`'s `U_mem_iff_scott`. -/
theorem V_mem_iff_finiteUnion {X : Set ℕ} :
    V.mem X ↔
      ∃ F : Finset (ℕ × ℕ), (∀ p ∈ F, p.2 < 2 ^ p.1) ∧ X = ⋃ p ∈ F, affine p.1 p.2 ∧ X.Nonempty := by
  constructor
  · rintro ⟨k, m, rfl, hne⟩
    refine ⟨(Finset.range (2 ^ k)).filter (fun ℓ => m.testBit ℓ) |>.image (fun ℓ => (k, ℓ)), ?_, ?_, hne⟩
    · rintro ⟨k', ℓ⟩ hp
      obtain ⟨ℓ', hℓ', heq⟩ := Finset.mem_image.mp hp
      obtain ⟨hlt, -⟩ := Finset.mem_filter.mp hℓ'
      simp only [Finset.mem_range] at hlt
      obtain ⟨rfl, rfl⟩ := Prod.mk.injEq .. ▸ heq
      exact hlt
    · rw [levelSet_eq_biUnion]
      ext n
      simp only [Set.mem_iUnion, Finset.mem_image, Finset.mem_filter, Finset.mem_range,
        exists_prop, exists_exists_and_eq_and]
  · rintro ⟨F, hbound, rfl, hne⟩
    have hf : ∀ p : F, affine p.1.1 p.1.2 = ∅ ∨ V.mem (affine p.1.1 p.1.2) :=
      fun ⟨p, hp⟩ => Or.inr ⟨p.1, 2 ^ p.2, affine_eq_levelSet p.1 p.2,
        affine_eq_levelSet p.1 p.2 ▸ affine_nonempty (hbound p hp)⟩
    have hrw : (⋃ p ∈ F, affine p.1 p.2) = ⋃ p : F, affine p.1.1 p.1.2 := by
      ext n; simp only [Set.mem_iUnion, exists_prop, Subtype.exists]
    rw [hrw] at hne ⊢
    exact V_iUnion_mem hf hne

end Scott1980.Neighborhood
